 he fought to protect overseas deserved the same advantage he had. He built it in his garage. The military sent lawyers. He redesigned it from the ground up to be completely legal while keeping every tactical capability intact. He called it VitalTac.\n\nVitalTac outperforms car headlights. It lights up your entire property like a stadium. It''s built from the same aerospace-grade aluminum and titanium alloy used on F-35 fighter jets, meaning you could use it as a striking weapon in close quarters and it won''t even dent. It''s waterproof. It works in freezing cold and extreme heat. You can run it over with a truck. Because at 2 AM when someone''s in your house, the one thing you grab has to work. Every single time. No exceptions.\n\nVitalTac''s built-in tactical strobe instantly disorients anyone caught in its beam ‚Äî the same strobe pattern used by SWAT teams during breaches. It buys you critical seconds to move your family, call 911, or position yourself. The SOS mode signals rescue from miles away if you''re ever stranded or in danger.\n\nBut I want you to think about something for a second. Right now, what''s actually on your nightstand? A phone? A glass of water? If someone kicks in your door tonight, what''s your plan for those 8 seconds? Because the intruder has a plan. And he''s counting on you not having one.\n\nHere''s what you need to know. The US Product Safety Commission is actively working to reclassify VitalTac as military-grade defense equipment. When that happens ‚Äî and multiple sources say it''s a matter of weeks, not months ‚Äî it gets pulled from civilian sale permanently. It''s already banned from Amazon and eBay. The only place left to get one is the official website.\n\nToday, for a limited time, you can get VitalTac at 50%% off. But I''ll be straight with you ‚Äî this page comes down the moment that regulation passes. Click the link now. Because the next time you hear a noise at 3 AM, you''re either going to reach for something that ends the threat instantly ‚Äî or you''re going to lie there in the dark, hoping it''s nothing. Make sure you never have to hope.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1034, '2026-01-30T16:32:13.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recPYGHsYR4NB0Vhs', 'GhostWing - Script 1017 - Nick', 'recMS4kpPubp6bHyu', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('Big drone companies don‚Äôt want you to know about this new $99 American military drone‚Äîbecause it‚Äôs so simple to fly that even people in their 60s and 70s are using it on their very first try.\nAnd that‚Äôs exactly why it‚Äôs such a threat.\nBecause for the first time ever, you don‚Äôt need fast reflexes, technical skills, or years of practice to fly a high-end drone.\nThis one was designed to do the hard work for you.\nIt was originally created for the U.S. Special Forces by Captain Adam Scott, a 44-year-old U.S. Army officer and lead engineer.\nHis team was given a critical mission in the Middle East.\nThey needed a drone that could capture enemy positions from miles away‚Ä¶\n while being so easy to control that it could be operated under extreme stress, in seconds, by anyone on the team.\nNo complicated controls.\n No learning curve.\n No second chances.\nAfter months of intense research and development, they created a groundbreaking prototype.\nAnd the results shocked everyone.\nIt was quickly celebrated as one of the most successful military inventions in recent years.\nWhy?\nBecause it was the first drone ever to use patented MOT military optical technology, making it at least 20 times more powerful than standard consumer drones‚Äîwhile being dramatically easier to operate.\nThis technology allows it to capture stunning 4K footage from incredible distances‚Ä¶\n without requiring precision flying or manual control.\nIn simple terms?\nYou don‚Äôt fly the drone.\nThe drone flies itself.\nAfter seeing how effortless it was to use, Adam realized something important.\nThis wasn‚Äôt just military tech.\nThis was technology the general public‚Äîespecially older Americans‚Äîhad been waiting for.\nSo he secured permission to redevelop the device for civilian use and prepared it for mass production.\nHe called it GhostWing.\nAnd it‚Äôs now being called the easiest high-performance drone ever made.\nGhostWing uses military-grade nanotechnology and advanced composite materials to match the quality of top drones that cost hundreds‚Äîor even thousands‚Äîof dollars.\nBut here‚Äôs the real breakthrough:\nAdam developed proprietary software that boosts stability and control by 120%%, making GhostWing so smooth and forgiving that literally anyone can fly it confidently within minutes.\nNo shaky hands.\n No panic controls.\n No crashes.\nIt even includes a ‚ÄúFollow Me‚Äù mode, so you don‚Äôt have to touch the controller at all.\nJust turn it on‚Ä¶\n and it automatically records beautiful, professional-looking footage of you and your surroundings.\nThe advanced GPS system tracks your location up to 900 meters, and if the signal weakens or the battery runs low, GhostWing automatically returns to you on its own.\nThe built-in collision detection prevents accidental crashes, which is why many owners say it‚Äôs the safest drone they‚Äôve ever used.\nAnd because it‚Äôs built with military-grade materials, it‚Äôs virtually indestructible.\nIt‚Äôs waterproof.\n It handles extreme heat and cold.\n And it‚Äôs tough enough to survive mistakes‚Äîbecause it assumes you‚Äôll never need to be perfect.\nThat‚Äôs why GhostWing is now being used for everything from capturing family memories‚Ä¶\n to checking property‚Ä¶\n to simply enjoying the feeling of flying‚Äîwithout stress or frustration.\nAnd the most surprising part?\nSome of GhostWing‚Äôs biggest fans are seniors who never thought they could fly a drone.\nHere‚Äôs what they‚Äôre saying:\n‚ÄúI‚Äôm 67 and flew it perfectly on my first try‚Äîno learning curve at all.‚Äù\n‚ÄúI avoided drones for years, but this one basically flies itself.‚Äù\n‚ÄúMy hands aren‚Äôt steady, yet the video came out smooth and professional.‚Äù\nWhen GhostWing first launched, it spread rapidly through military and engineering circles.\nBut once everyday people‚Äîespecially older users‚Äîstarted sharing their footage online, everything changed.\nThe videos went viral.\nAnd GhostWing sold out in just 48 hours, creating a waitlist of over 10,000 orders worldwide.\nPhotographers, filmmakers, retirees, and families all rushed to get one.\nNow, to make this technology available to as many people as possible, Adam has tripled production and is offering a limited 50%% discount for the next 24 hours.\nAnd if you order more than one, the savings go even deeper‚Äîmaking it a perfect gift for family members who‚Äôve always wanted a drone, but thought they were ‚Äútoo old‚Äù to use one.\nMy honest advice?\nGet one for yourself‚Ä¶\n and one for someone you love‚Ä¶\n before this offer disappears.\nClick the link below this video now and secure your GhostWing with 50%% off, while it‚Äôs still available.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1017, '2026-01-05T15:51:02.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recQexY15Q1zbTQuV', 'VitalTac - Script 1054 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('My unit called it the sun gun. Now I own three.\n\nI served 8 years as an Army Ranger. We carried a tactical flashlight that could turn midnight into noon. It could blind enemy combatants, signal helicopters, and survive explosions. We trusted it with our lives on every mission.\n\nWhen I got out, I tried to buy one for home. Couldn''t find it anywhere. The military doesn''t sell to civilians. So I started using commercial flashlights.\n\nThey were garbage. Dim. Fragile. Dead batteries every other week. Nothing even close to what I had overseas.\n\nThen my buddy told me about VitalTac.\n\nAn ex-special forces operator named Mike had rebuilt the military flashlight for civilian use. Same technology. Same materials. Same blinding power. But legal for Americans to own.\n\nI was skeptical. I''d been burned by tacticool gear before. So I ordered one just to see.\n\nFirst time I turned it on, I was back in Afghanistan. That beam. That intensity. That feeling of having real equipment in your hands. This was the real thing.\n\nVitalTac uses military-grade Cree LEDs that produce 20 times the output of anything at Home Depot. The beam reaches 2 miles. The body is forged from aircraft-grade titanium and aluminum, same materials they use on fifth-generation fighters.\n\nWatch it destroy car headlights. That''s not a trick. That''s engineering.\n\nI''ve tested this flashlight hard. Dropped it in my pool. Left it in my truck during a Texas summer. Froze it in my garage over winter. Threw it against concrete. Still works perfectly.\n\nThe strobe function is what we used overseas to disorient threats. Flash it in someone''s face and they can''t see for minutes. No permanent damage