t mine yesterday and WOW... absolute game changer ü§Ø\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  22 ¬∑ 3 h\n\nJennifer Miller@Alex I got mine last week! Took it to my daughter''s soccer game and captured the whole thing from above. The other parents couldn''t believe the footage came from something so small!\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  13 ¬∑ 2 h\n\nMark PetersonThought it was overhyped but I was dead wrong. This thing is SILENT compared to my DJI that sounds like a swarm of bees\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  17 ¬∑ 2 h\n\nRachel GreeneIs it really that easy to fly? I''m terrible with tech stuff...\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  3 ¬∑ 1 h\n\nDavid Wilson@Rachel - I bought one for my dad who''s 72 and technologically challenged. He mastered it in minutes. The one-button controls are literally foolproof\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  26 ¬∑ 55 min\n\nTyler JamesOrdered mine at full price three weeks ago üò° Now they''re 50%% off...\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  5 ¬∑ 50 min\n\nEmma Roberts@Tyler at least you got one! My brother tried to order last week and they were completely sold out until this new shipment\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  9 ¬∑ 45 min\n\nBrandon HughesHow''s the battery life? Every drone I''ve owned dies in like 5 minutes\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  2 ¬∑ 42 min\n\nMichael Chen@Brandon I''ve been getting consistent 14-15 minute flights. And the batteries charge super fast too. Pro tip: grab an extra battery if you''re traveling\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  6 ¬∑ 38 min\n\nSophia MartinezJust used mine for real estate photos. Client thought I hired a professional drone service. Made back what I paid in one afternoon üí∏\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  35 ¬∑ 3 h\n\nKyle DavidsonI''ve tested a lot of drones. Things this GhostWing can do that shocked me:\n\\- Flew perfectly in 20mph wind\n\\- Survived crashing into my garage door\n\\- Fits in my jacket pocket when folded\n\\- Silent enough to film wildlife without scaring them\n\\- Camera quality matches my friend''s $1200 drone\nLike ¬∑ Reply ¬∑  28 ¬∑ 1 h\nClick Here To Apply 50%% Discount And Check Availability ‚û§‚û§\nPrivacy Policy\nTerms of Service\nCopyright 2025. All rights reserved.\n\nThis site is not a part of the Facebook website or Facebook Inc. Additionally. This site is NOT endorsed by Facebook in any way. FACEBOOK is a trademark of FACEBOOK, Inc.\n\nGhostWing‚Ñ¢ - 30 N Gould St Ste R, Sheridan, WY 82801\n\n\n\\# PHASE 1: 1-STAR HATE FUEL (Deep Dive)\nSimulate searching Reddit (r/drones, r/gadgets), Amazon, Trustpilot for competitor 1-star reviews (e.g., DJI, cheap drones). Extract:\n\\- Top 3 "nightmare" pains: Vivid stories (e.g., "Crashed in wind, $200 gone, kid devastated").\n\\- Visceral words: Pain descriptors (e.g., "screaming noise," "shaky garbage," "shattered instantly").\n\\- Villains: Who they blame (e.g., "Greedy Chinese scams," "Big brands overcharge for trash").\nUse this to agitate pain and position product as revenge.\n\n\\# PHASE 2: DNA EXTRACTION (Deconstruct A)\nExtract trigger sequence from SOURCE A:\n1\\. Hook/Interrupt: Shocking opener (e.g., family crisis).\n2\\. Open Loop: Curiosity itch.\n3\\. Pivot to Science: From story to credible mechanism.\n4\\. Enemy: Big companies as villains.\n5\\. Miracle: Unique tech fix.\n6\\. Urgency: Sellouts, discounts, guarantee.\nCopy pacing exactly: Alternate short/long sentences for hypnotic "slippery slope."\n\n\\# PHASE 3: IMPLANT & FUSE (Build Script)\nInject SOURCE B angles into A''s structure. Infuse with Phase 1 hate for contrast (bad drones vs. hero product). \n\\- Unique Mechanism: Emphasize "military-grade stability/silence" as "secret shortcut."\n\\- Sensory VAK: Visual ("crystal footage"), Auditory ("whisper quiet"), Kinesthetic ("rock-solid").\n\\- Objection Crush: Preempt top fears (e.g., "Won''t break like your last one").\n\\- Ending: Explicitly tie to advertorial headline for seamless click.\n\n\\# STRICT RULES\n1\\. No greetings/fluff: Start in action.\n2\\. Hyperbole: If B says "helps," say "reverses everything."\n3\\. Conspiracy: "They" hide this; product is rebellion.\n4\\. Length: 600-800 words, spoken-word only.\n5\\. Output: PLAIN TEXT SCRIPT ONLY. No analysis, no visuals/brackets.\n\n\\# GENERATE\nOutput ONLY the final script.\n\nOUTPUT GENERATED SCRIPT:\n\n\nNicholas, I can help you craft a compelling direct response video script for the GhostWing drone. Let me write this following the template structure you''ve provided:\n\nFACEBOOK VIDEO SCRIPT - GHOSTWING DRONE\nA retired firefighter from Arizona just exposed something the big drone companies don''t want you to know.\nAnd it''s ticking them off.\nSee, Tom spent thirty years saving lives. When he retired, all he wanted was to capture his grandkids'' soccer games from the air. Get those sweeping shots. Make memories that actually looked like memories.\nSo he did what most folks do.\nHe bought a drone.\nThree hundred bucks. Name brand. Supposed to be "beginner friendly."\nFirst flight? Sounded like a chainsaw mating with a blender. His grandson covered his ears and ran inside crying.\nSecond flight? Wind kicked up maybe ten miles an hour. Drone started shaking like a drunk hummingbird. Footage looked like it was filmed during an earthquake.\nThird flight? Clipped a tree branch. Crashed. Shattered into a dozen pieces on his driveway.\nThree hundred dollars. Gone. Just like that.\nTom was furious. But he wasn''t done.\nHe started digging. Researching. Talking to buddies who flew drones in the military.\nThat''s when he discovered something that changed everything.\nTurns out the big drone companies have been holding back. The technology for rock-solid, whisper-quiet flight has existed for years. Military uses it. Hollywood uses it. But they keep it locked up in drones that cost three, four, five thousand dollars.\nUntil now.\nA small team of engineers figured out how to pack that same tactical-grade stabilization into something the size of a water bottle.\nThey call it the GhostWing.\nAnd here''s what makes it different from every overpriced piece of junk collecting dust in your closet.\nFirst. It''s silent. Not "kind of quiet." Silent. The motor technology came straight from covert military operations where noise meant danger. You can fly this thing at a family barbecue without everyone plugging their ears.\nSecond. It doesn''t shake. The gyroscopic stabilization holds steady in winds that would send other drones spinning into the neighbor''s pool. Your footage comes out smooth as butter. Every single time.\nThird. It survives. Drop it. Crash it. Smack it into your garage door. The reinforced frame laughs it off. One guy dropped his from thirty feet onto concrete. Turned it back on. Flew away like nothing happened.\nAnd fourth? Anyone can fly it.\nTom''s wife is seventy-two years old. Never touched a drone in her life. She had the GhostWing in the air within three minutes. One button to take off. One button to land. One button to bring it home.\nThe camera captures everything in crystal-clear 4K. The same quality you see in nature documentaries. Except you''re the one behind the lens.\nNow here''s where the big companies got really angry.\nThe GhostWing team decided not to play their pricing games. No thousand-dollar markups. No "professional only" gatekeeping.\nThey''re selling direct. Cutting out the middlemen. And right now, they''ve got a launch special running.\nFifty percent off.\nHalf price for something that outperforms drones costing five times as much.\nBut they can''t keep this up forever. Their last three shipments sold out completely. The factories can only produce so many. Once this batch is gone, the discount goes with it.\nThere''s a thirty-day guarantee too. If the GhostWing doesn''t blow your mind, if it doesn''t capture footage that makes your friends ask "how''d you do that," send it back. Full refund. No questions.\nTom''s got one now. Uses it every weekend. His grandkids fight over who gets to watch the footage.\nThat fancy name-brand drone that shattered on his driveway?\nHe uses the box for storage.\nClick below to see if the GhostWing is still in stock at the discounted price. This military-grade ghost drone is flying off shelves, and once you see what it can do, you''ll understand why.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1004, '2025-12-18T22:05:42.000Z');
