20%%, making it a true one-button drone that literally anyone can fly on their very first try.\n\nIt''s loaded with cutting-edge technology like the Follow Me feature, which lets you take amazing videos of yourself without even touching the controller. The advanced GPS functionality means it can track your location within 900 meters and return to you quickly if the signal is weak or the battery gets low. You never have to worry about losing it.\n\nThe collision detection function prevents any accidental crash or damage, making this drone the safest quadcopter ever engineered. It''s literally impossible to crash. And because it''s made of the best military materials available, it''s virtually indestructible. It''s completely waterproof and strong enough to withstand both freezing cold and scorching hot temperatures.\n\nAnd what''s best about this drone is that you can use it for thousands of different purposes. Whether you''re excited about turning your social media profile into a viral sensation, or you want to capture precious memories with your family, the possibilities with the GhostWing are endless. It''s also a perfect security tool, allowing you to monitor your property from a safe distance.\n\nWhen Adam first launched GhostWing, it spread like wildfire in the military community. What he didn''t expect was for everyone to start sharing the incredible footage they shot with the GhostWing all over the internet. After going viral, it sold out within the first 48 hours and quickly developed a waitlist of over 10,000 orders from all around the world. Celebrities, professional photographers, and filmmakers have all made the switch to it.\n\nAdam wants everyone to know about this new technology, so he has tripled production and is offering a 50%% discount for anyone who orders within the next 24 hours. You can get even deeper discounts by ordering multiple GhostWings, making it a perfect gift for anyone.\n\nMy advice: grab one for yourself and a few more for your friends and family before this amazing deal is taken down. Click on the link below this video to visit the official website and order with 50%% off.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1045, '2026-01-18T09:01:07.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recWret8UltabIFuI', 'VitalTac - Script 1038 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('40 million people have watched this video in the last two weeks. A Special Forces veteran holds up a flashlight the size of an iPhone, points it at a piece of cardboard, and within seconds ‚Äî the cardboard is on fire. Not from a laser. Not from a heating element. From the flashlight beam alone. Two days after the video went viral, Amazon permanently banned the product. The US government opened a file to classify it as military equipment. And right now, you can still buy one. But probably not for long.\n\nThe flashlight is called VitalTac. And the reason 40 million people can''t stop watching that video isn''t because of a magic trick ‚Äî it''s because most people had no idea this technology existed outside the military. Neither did I. So I did what any rational person would do. I looked into it.\n\nHere''s what I found.\n\nVitalTac uses military-grade Cree LED technology that produces a beam at least 20 times more powerful than the strongest flashlight available in any store, anywhere. The beam reaches 2 miles. At close range ‚Äî hallway distance, staircase distance ‚Äî it completely overwhelms human vision. Military terminology for this is "hard blind" ‚Äî the target''s visual cortex is so overloaded that they lose spatial orientation entirely. They can''t see, can''t balance, can''t move toward you. That''s not a flashlight. That''s a tactical system.\n\nThis technology was developed specifically for American Special Forces units conducting night operations in enemy territory. It was classified. It was restricted. And it was devastatingly effective ‚Äî which is exactly why a combat veteran with three tours decided the American public deserved access to it.\n\nHe built the civilian version in his garage. The military responded with legal threats. He modified every component until it was completely legal ‚Äî while preserving every tactical function that made Special Forces operators rely on it in life-or-death situations. He called it VitalTac, and he''s the only authorized manufacturer in the United States.\n\nVitalTac is constructed from the same aerospace-grade aluminum and titanium alloy used on fifth-generation fighter jets. This isn''t marketing language ‚Äî it''s the same Grade-5 titanium specification. That means it''s virtually indestructible. Waterproof to extreme depth. Operational in freezing cold and extreme heat. It survives impacts that would shatter any commercial flashlight into pieces. You can use it as a close-quarters striking tool and it won''t even mark. 12-hour rechargeable battery. Instant-on activation. No fumbling, no warm-up, no failure.\n\nThe tactical strobe replicates SWAT breach protocols ‚Äî it hijacks the intruder''s nervous system, buying you critical seconds to protect your family, establish a defensive position, or call for help. The SOS function is visible from miles away, including from search aircraft.\n\nHere''s what most people don''t realize about that viral video. The veteran didn''t post it to sell flashlights. He posted it because he was angry. He was angry that the technology he relied on to protect American interests overseas was being kept from the American people who paid for it. His exact words in the video: "If this was good enough to protect me in a warzone, why isn''t it good enough to protect your family at home?" That''s the video the government wants taken down. That''s what Amazon banned. Not because it''s dangerous to own ‚Äî because it''s embarrassing that civilians didn''t have access sooner.\n\nThe reclassification is happening. Multiple sources inside the Product Safety Commission have confirmed it''s a matter of weeks. When it goes through, VitalTac gets pulled from civilian sale. Permanently. Every listing, gone. Every unit in production, redirected to military contracts. The only people who will have one are the people who ordered before the cutoff.\n\nRight now, VitalTac is 50%% off on the official website ‚Äî the only place left that sells it. Click the link. 40 million people have already seen what this thing can do. The only difference between you and them is that you still have a chance to own one.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1038, '2026-01-30T16:50:00.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recWts9hOCg8wB2l6', 'VitalTac - Script 1022 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('This new military flashlight is so powerful it can blind a bear.\n\nHowever, be warned, this flashlight is not a toy. It‚Äôs basically a handheld weapon that fits in your pack. It''s so powerful that it can illuminate tree lines from hundreds of yards away and even start a fire if your lighter gets wet, making it the ultimate tool for anyone who takes the backcountry seriously. The flashlight projects an incredibly powerful beam of light reaching up to 2 miles, meaning you can spot eyes in the darkness, find your trail, or signal your hunting party from ridgelines away. It was designed specifically for American special forces conducting operations in dense wilderness and hostile terrain at night, where navigation and threat identification in zero visibility was life or death. The flashlight features state-of-the-art military-grade Cree''s LED technology, making it at least 20 times more powerful than those hunting lights that can barely reach across a field, which gives it the throw distance you actually need when you''re miles from the truck and the sun went down an hour ago. It literally turns night into day wherever you point it. It was designed for special forces and couldn''t be sold to civilians. That is, until a few weeks ago, when an ex-special forces operator who grew up hunting and fishing redesigned the flashlight for outdoor use while retaining all its field-proven functions. He remembered what it was like navigating back to camp with a dying flashlight and knew hunters and outdoorsmen deserved better equipment. He loved these flashlights when he was serving his country, memorized the design and technology so he could build one for serious outdoor use. 