ecification. Impact-resistant to military specification. I''ve seen these survive being run over by trucks.\n\nYour tactical flashlight can''t start a fire. VitalTac can. Concentrated light intense enough to ignite kindling in seconds. No matches needed.\n\nYour tactical flashlight has a strobe mode that''s basically a party trick. VitalTac''s strobe can instantly blind and disorient threats. It''s what operators use instead of firing a weapon.\n\nHere''s what''s happening.\n\nThe Product Safety Commission wants to classify VitalTac as military equipment. Real military equipment. Because that''s what it is. Once that happens, no more online sales. It''s already banned from Amazon and eBay. You can only get it from Mike''s official website.\n\nThe military version is $600. Mike could charge $300 and sell every unit. But he built this for regular Americans who''ve been lied to by flashlight marketing for years.\n\nRight now he''s offering VitalTac at 50%% off.\n\nThink about how many cheap flashlights you''ve bought. How many have broken. How many have disappointed you. How much money you''ve wasted on garbage that couldn''t perform when it mattered.\n\nThis is your chance to buy once and never worry again.\n\nClick the link below this video. See the real demonstrations. And get yours before the discount ends.\n\nStop settling for toys marketed as tools.\n\nClick now.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1057, '2026-02-19T17:50:24.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recau0DQQXRMQ6BK8', 'VitalTac - Script 1049 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('A father in Houston kept his three kids safe for eleven days with no power, no heat, and one flashlight that''s now been banned from Amazon.\n\nNight two is when the looting started. He could hear them ‚Äî boots on glass two streets over, flashlight beams sweeping driveways, car doors getting tested one by one. His wife was holding their youngest in the hallway. His nine-year-old kept asking why the neighbors were screaming. And this man ‚Äî a pipe fitter, not a soldier ‚Äî walked to his front porch, raised one flashlight, and turned his entire front yard into daylight so bright the group across the street shielded their faces and kept moving. They didn''t come back.\n\nThat flashlight was built by a Special Forces operator who came home from his third combat tour and couldn''t sleep for a reason nobody talks about. It wasn''t the missions. It was his daughter. She was five. And one night during a rolling blackout in Fort Bragg housing, she woke up crying in pitch dark and he couldn''t get to her fast enough with the garbage flashlight in his kitchen drawer. He said that''s when it hit him ‚Äî he''d carried a light overseas that could turn midnight into noon, that could freeze a hostile in a doorway from thirty feet away, that could signal a helicopter from two miles out ‚Äî and his own little girl had nothing. His family had nothing. So he built it. He called it VitalTac. And the military sent lawyers to his door within a week.\n\nHe redesigned every component. Made it completely legal for civilians. But he kept every tactical function intact.\n\nThe body is machined from the same aerospace-grade aluminum and titanium they use on F-35 fighter jets. You can drop it