INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recdg7zkCsdAkWtE6', 'VitalTac - Script 1047 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('My daughter was screaming my name in the dark‚Ä¶ and I couldn''t find her.\n\nThat''s what a father from Tulsa told me last month. October ice storm knocked out power for six days. His seven-year-old wandered out the back door in the blackout looking for their dog.\n\nHe grabbed the flashlight from the junk drawer. Dead batteries. Grabbed his phone. Four percent battery. He spent eleven minutes stumbling through his own backyard ‚Äî a yard he''s mowed every Sunday for nine years ‚Äî calling her name, tripping over the fence line, completely blind.\n\nHis neighbor found her. Not him. His neighbor.\n\nHe told me, "I''ve never felt that small in my life."\n\nAnd if you''re a father listening to this, that sentence just hit you somewhere. Because you know the deal you made with yourself the day you held your kid for the first time. You''d be ready. You''d be the one they count on. You''d never be the guy fumbling in the dark while someone else steps up.\n\nBut here''s the truth most men won''t say out loud: you are not prepared. Not even close.\n\nThat''s why a retired Special Forces operator ‚Äî a guy who ran night missions in places the government still won''t name ‚Äî built something for men like us. He called it the VitalTac.\n\nThis is not a flashlight you pick up at the hardware store. This is the same technology used in fifth-generation fighter jets. The body is machined from purified aircraft-grade aluminum and titanium. It is waterproof. It is indestructible. You can run it over with a truck, pull it out of a lake, use it at forty below zero. It does not care.\n\nThe beam reaches two miles. Two miles. That''s not "checking the backyard." That''s finding your kid, lighting up a threat three blocks away, signaling rescue from a rooftop during a flood. The strobe mode alone will shut down the nervous system of anyone who shouldn''t be near your family. Temporarily blind them. Buy you time. End the situation.\n\nA father in Houston used one during Hurricane Beryl to guide paramedics to his wife who''d gone into labor during the blackout. He said, "That light did what I couldn''t do alone."\n\nNow here''s the problem. The US Product Safety Commission is reviewing whether civilians should have access to this level of output. It''s already banned from Amazon and eBay ‚Äî too powerful for their liability standards. That means you cannot find this in any store and you won''t find it on any marketplace.\n\nRight now, the only place to get the VitalTac is from the official site, and they''re running a limited release at fifty percent off ‚Äî as low as twenty-seven dollars for the men who are smart enough to grab more than one.\n\nThe last batch sold out in four hours. I''m not saying that to pressure you. I''m saying it because the father in Tulsa told me he waited, and he''ll regret that for the rest of his life.\n\nYou made a promise the day you became a father. A husband. The man your family looks to when the lights go out and the world stops making sense.\n\nDon''t be the man fumbling in the dark.\n\nTap the link below, get the VitalTac while it''s still available ‚Äî and never be unprepared again.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1047, '2026-01-30T17:41:36.000Z');
