from angles no one else can get. Capture your fishing trip, your garden in full bloom. GhostWing makes sure you never miss a moment.\n\nIt sold out in 48 hours. Over 10,000 orders hit the waitlist. 4.9 stars across 15,000-plus reviews. Celebrities, professional photographers, and filmmakers all made the switch. Adam has restocked and is offering 50 percent off right now for anyone who orders in the next 24 hours. Just $99. At this price, the last batch disappeared in 48 hours ‚Äî this one won''t last either. Order more than one and discounts get even bigger, making it the perfect gift. Every order is backed by a 30-day guarantee. Zero risk.\n\nClick the link below this video and grab yours at 50 percent off before this deal is gone. Then come back and drop a comment telling everyone what you flew over first. Tag someone who needs to stop paying $300 for roof inspections.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1080, '2026-02-19T03:24:12.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recfLd2YIKDxRDErX', 'VitalTac - Script 1066 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('This video got 12 million views in three days. A guy melting a hole through a soda can with a flashlight.\n\nNot a laser. Not a torch. A flashlight.\n\nThe comments exploded. "Fake." "CGI." "No way this is real."\n\nIt''s real. And I''m going to show you exactly what this thing is.\n\nThis is VitalTac. The beam you''re seeing produces more concentrated light than anything available to civilians. The military-grade Cree LEDs output twenty times more power than commercial flashlights. At close range, the thermal energy is intense enough to scorch wood, melt thin plastic, and ignite dry material in seconds.\n\nWatch this. That''s a real-time demonstration. No edits. No tricks. Just physics.\n\nThe video went viral because people couldn''t believe something this powerful exists outside of military applications. And until recently, it didn''t. This technology was classified. Built for Special Forces conducting operations in total darkness where the flashlight wasn''t just a tool ‚Äî it was a weapon.\n\nOne operator who''d carried this through three combat tours came home and decided his family deserved the same protection. He rebuilt the design. The government sent lawyers. He modified it to be legal while keeping every capability intact.\n\nHe called it VitalTac.\n\nThe specs are insane. Two-mile beam range. Aerospace-grade titanium body ‚Äî the same material on stealth fighters. Waterproof. Freezeproof. Literally indestructible. The strobe function can completely disorient anyone caught in its beam. The SOS mode signals rescue from miles away.\n\nBut here''s what the viral video didn''t explain.\n\nThis is a home defense weapon that doesn''t require a permit, background check, or training. Point it at an intruder and their vision is gone. They can''t see you. They can''t advance. They can''t do anything except cover their eyes and retreat.\n\nNo shots fired. No legal battles. No trauma for your kids.\n\nThe video also didn''t mention that this is disappearing.\n\nThe Product Safety Commission wants to classify VitalTac as military-grade defense equipment. When that regulation passes ‚Äî and multiple sources say it''s imminent ‚Äî civilian sales end. Permanently. It''s already banned from Amazon and eBay. The only source is the official website.\n\nThat viral video drove so much traffic that inventory dropped by 60%% in a week. I don''t know how much is left.\n\nWhat I do know is this: right now, today, they''re offering 50%% off. That''s the same technology Special Forces uses to dominate in darkness, at a price that doesn''t require a second mortgage.\n\nThe comments on that video were split between "this is fake" and "where do I buy one." If you''re in the second group, click the link below.\n\nWatch the full demonstrations on the official page. See the beam comparisons. See the durability tests. See why 12 million people stopped scrolling.\n\nThen get yours before the video stops being a product demo and starts being a historical artifact of something civilians used to be able to buy.\n\nClick now.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1066, '2026-02-20T11:44:36.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recfdqMDBrM0OV51S', 'VitalTac - Script 1025 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('Amazon banned this flashlight and called it "too dangerous for civilians." It''s so powerful that it can start fires in seconds, light up targets from two miles away, and blind anyone who threatens you ‚Äî all from something the size of your phone. \n\nIt was created specifically for the US Special Forces by Sergeant Kyle Mitchell, a 41-year-old Army combat engineer who spent 15 years developing tactical equipment for the most dangerous missions on earth. He and his team were assigned to create a light source powerful enough to disorient enemy combatants, signal extraction helicopters from miles away, and survive the worst conditions imaginable. The mission required something that had never existed before ‚Äî a flashlight so powerful it could be used as a weapon. After months of research and development, they created a groundbreaking prototype and the results were incredible, celebrated as the most successful tactical illumination device in military history. It was the first to ever use classified military optical technology, meaning it''s at least 20 times more powerful than any flashlight you can buy at Walmart or Home Depot, which gives it incredible capability.\nIt can literally burn through cardboard, cook food, and light up your entire property like it''s the middle of the day. After seeing the incredible potential of this technology, Kyle quickly realized that regular people needed this even more than soldiers did. Think about it ‚Äî when the power goes out, when your car breaks down on a dark road, when someone''s breaking into your house at 3am ‚Äî that''s when you need real power, not some cheap dollar store garbage that dies after ten minutes. So he decided to make this device available to anyone smart enough to grab one. As the original creator of the technology, he quickly secured all the permissions needed to redevelop the device and ready it for mass production. He called it VitalTac, and it''s the most powerful flashlight ever made available to the public. It uses a combination of military-grade optical technology and the same titanium they put in fighter jets to achieve the level of quality and durability that the military was paying over $400 for, but at a price anyone can afford. Kyle developed a specialized beam system that concentrates light 20 times more powerfully than regular flashlights, making it so intense that it can ignite dry kindling in seconds flat. It''s loaded with cutting-edge features like the tactical strobe mode, which lets you completely blind and disorient any threat without ever touching them ‚Äî the same technique soldiers use in combat. The SOS functionality means rescue crews and aircraft can spot your signal from miles away, even in the worst conditions. The waterproof construction means you can drop it in a lake, leave it underwater for hours, and it still works perfectly, making this the most indestructible flashlight ever engineered. And because it''s built from Grade-5 titanium ‚Äî the same stuff in fighter jets ‚Äî you can run it over with your truck, drop it off a roof, or beat it against concrete and it won''t even scratch.\nIt runs for 12 full hours on a single charge and uses the same USB cable as your phone, so you never have to hunt for batteries again. And what''s best about this flashlight is that you can use it for literally anything. Whether you''re dealing with a blackout and need to light up your whole house, stranded on the highway and need someone to see you, camping in the woods and need to start a fire without matches, or face-to-face with someone who means you harm and need to blind them instantly ‚Äî the VitalTac handles it all. It''s the ultimate tool for anyone who refuses to be caught helpless in the dark. When Kyle first launched VitalTac, it spread like wildfire through the military and prepper communities.\nWhat he didn''t expect was for a Special Forces veteran to post a video showing the VitalTac burning a hole through cardboard in ten seconds flat. After that video went viral, it sold out within 48 hours and developed a waitlist of over 10,000 people from all around the world. The attention got so intense that Amazon actually banned it from their website ‚Äî they called it "too powerful" and "potentially dangerous." Former soldiers, truckers, hunters, and regular folks who just want to protect their families all rushed to get one before they couldn''t anymore. Kyle wants everyone to have the chance to own this technology before new regulations make it illegal, so he has tripled production and is offering a 50%% discount for anyone who orders right now. You can get even bigger savings by ordering multiple VitalTacs ‚Äî pay just $40 each when you buy two, $36 each when you buy three, or only $27 each when you grab five ‚Äî making it the perfect gift for anyone you care about. My advice? Get one for your car, one for your nightstand, one for your emergency kit, and a few more for your family members ‚Äî because when the lights go out and you''re standing in the dark, it''s too late to wish you had one. Click the link below this video to visit the official website and order with 50%% off before the government decides regular Americans shouldn''t be allowed to own something this powerful.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1025, '2026-01-05T15:45:04.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recfiXdet0VByGrSp', 'GhostWing - Script 1086 - Nick', 'recMS4kpPubp6bHyu', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('Think you''re too old to fly a drone?\n\nThat''s exactly what the big drone companies want you to believe.\n\nThey design their products for 25-year-old tech bros. Complicated apps. Confusing controls. Tiny buttons that require perfect eyesight. Then they blame YOU when their overpriced junk crashes into a tree.\n\nBut here''s what they don''t want you to know.\n\nThe most advanced drone ever created is also the easiest to fly. And a 78-year-old grandmother in Ohio just proved it.\n\nHer name is Dorothy. Never owned a smartphone until two years ago. Still calls her grandson when her email won''t load. Last month, her son bought her something called a GhostWing.\n\nShe had it flying in 90 seconds.\n\nNot because Dorothy suddenly became a tech genius. Because the GhostWing was designed by someone who actually understands how real people think.\n\nCaptain Adam Scott spent years developing classified drone technology for US Special Forces. His team created equipment that could capture enemy positions from miles away without detection. It used something called MOT military optical technology, making it 20 times more powerful than anything on the civilian market.\n\nBut here''s what made Adam different from other military engineers.\n\nHe watched his own 73-year-old father struggle with a consumer drone. Watched him get frustrated. Watched him give up. And Adam realized the problem wasn''t his father.\n\nThe problem was the drone industry.\n\nSo Adam took his military technology and stripped out all the complexity. He kept only what matters: stunning footage, rock-solid stability, and controls so simple that his father flew it perfectly on his very first attempt.\n\nOne