terials, the thing is virtually indestructible. Waterproof. Temperature resistant. One customer dropped his from thirty feet. Turned it back on. Kept flying.\n\nMy grandmother uses hers every week now. She films her garden. Family gatherings. Her great-grandchildren running around the yard. The footage looks professional.\n\nHer friends at the senior center saw the videos. Five of them ordered GhostWings within a month. The youngest is 68. The oldest is 81. Every single one was flying within minutes of opening the box.\n\nWhen GhostWing first launched, it sold out in 48 hours. The waitlist hit 10,000 orders from around the world. It spread like wildfire through the military community because veterans recognized the technology immediately.\n\nNow Adam has tripled production. And he''s offering a 50%% discount for anyone who orders in the next 24 hours.\n\nI bought one for myself after seeing my grandmother''s footage. I bought two more as gifts.\n\nIf you''ve ever thought drones were too complicated for you, think again. If a 74-year-old woman who calls her TV the picture box can master this in seconds, so can you.\n\nClick the link below to visit the official GhostWing website and claim your 50%% discount before this batch sells out. The technology you''ve been waiting for is finally here.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1089, '2026-02-19T17:33:14.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recscv99jd4oBAKvE', 'GhostWing - Script 1082 - Nick', 'recMS4kpPubp6bHyu', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('My grandson bought me my first drone for my birthday. I crashed it into the neighbor''s fence in 14 seconds flat. He laughed. I laughed. But I felt like a fool. So I did something he never expected. I bought him a drone back ‚Äî a strange little $99 military drone I saw online. He unfolded it, pressed one button, and his jaw hit the floor. "Grandpa, how is this thing flying itself?" Now my 14-year-old grandson asks ME for flying tips. And I''m 74 years old.\n\nHere''s what nobody tells you. Millions of Americans over 55 have bought drones. DJI. Autel. Brands that cost $400, $800, even $1,200. And almost every single one of those drones is sitting in a closet right now. Gathering dust. Because the controllers have 30 buttons. The apps crash. The instructions read like a college textbook. You watched the YouTube tutorials. You handed the controller to your grandson and said "you do it." You called the 1-800 number and sat on hold for 45 minutes. Nothing worked. And deep down, a voice whispered something cruel: maybe this technology just isn''t for people like you.\n\nThat voice was wrong. The technology was wrong. You weren''t.\n\nBecause a 44-year-old US Army officer named Captain Adam Scott built something that changed everything. His team was assigned to develop advanced optical equipment for a critical Special Forces mission in the Middle East. They needed to capture enemy positions from miles away without detection. After months of development, they created a breakthrough that became one of the most celebrated military inventions in recent years ‚Äî the first device to use patented MOT military optical technology, making it at least 20 times more powerful than any commercial drone, with stunning 4K clarity.\n\nThen Adam had a simple thought. If a soldier under enemy fire could operate this drone with zero training, why couldn''t a retired grandfather in Michigan fly it from a lawn chair? So he secured every permission needed, redesigned it for everyday Americans, and called it GhostWing.\n\nGhostWing is the easiest drone ever made. You tap one button. That''s it. It rises, it hovers, it waits for you. The software increases power and control by 120 percent, so the drone practically flies itself. You just point where you want it to go. The follow-me feature captures video of you automatically ‚Äî no piloting skill needed, not one single button to learn. The 4K camera captures footage so sharp you can count individual roof shingles from 400 feet up. The GPS tracks your location within 900 meters and brings GhostWing straight back to your hand when the battery gets low. It literally cannot get lost. Collision detection makes it impossible to crash, even on your very first flight. Built from military-grade carbon-polymer materials. Waterproof. Survives freezing winters and brutal summers. Folds smaller than a water bottle. Flies 70 percent quieter than competitors. 2.7-mile range. 15 minutes of flight time.\n\nNow picture your Saturday morning. You press one button. GhostWing rises straight up. Your phone shows a crystal-clear view of your entire roof ‚Äî every shingle, every gutter ‚Äî no ladder, no $300 inspection fee. Your grandkids chase each other across the yard and GhostWing follows them automatically, capturing footage you''ll replay a thousand times. You survey your whole property line in minutes. You check your home security from the couch. On vacation, you capture memories that look like a Hollywood film. And when your grandson visits and sees the footage, he says the five words every grandparent lives for: "Can you teach me, Grandpa?"\n\nGhostWing has earned 4.9 stars from over 15,000 reviews. It sold out in 48 hours and built a waitlist of 10,000 orders worldwide. Celebrities, professional photographers, and filmmakers have all made the switch. Tag someone over 55 who needs to see this.\n\nGhostWing sold out in 48 hours the first time around and 10,000 people joined the waitlist. Captain Scott has restocked and is offering 50 percent off for the next 24 hours ‚Äî just $99. At this price, this batch won''t last long either. Order multiple GhostWings for even bigger discounts, all backed by a 30-day guarantee. Grab one for yourself and one for the grandson who still can''t believe Grandpa flies better than he does. Click the link below to visit the official site and order at 50 percent off before this batch is gone.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1082, '2026-02-19T03:24:48.000Z');
