in the US, he chose to call his product VitalTac. VitalTac is the most powerful flashlight ever made. Check out the difference yourself. It even beats a car''s headlights with ease. VitalTac is made from the same purified aluminum and titanium they use on the latest fifth-generation fighter aircraft to withstand enormous pressure and heat. Meaning that the VitalTac is indestructible.\nIt''s completely waterproof and strong enough to withstand both freezing temperatures, boiling water, as well as flaming hot fire. You can even run it over, and it will keep working. This flashlight is the perfect survival tool. Its light beam is even powerful enough to cook food, like an egg. The VitalTac even has a strobe and SOS function, perfect for emergency situations where visibility is key to survival.\nIf you are interested in the VitalTac, there''s something you should know. While completely legal, this flashlight is not a toy as it''s extremely powerful. The US Product Safety Commission is trying to classify it as military-grade defense equipment. While it will remain perfectly legal to own one, it probably won''t be long before it''s taken off the online market. That''s also the reason why you can''t buy it from web stores like Amazon or eBay. In fact, if you really want one, you can only order it from the official website, and today only you can get yours with a 50%% discount. Click the link in this video for more information about the VitalTac.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1001, '2025-12-25T18:00:56.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('rectsyDOkQj4nmO82', 'GhostWing - Script 1046 - Nick', 'recMS4kpPubp6bHyu', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('Drone companies said people over 60 couldn''t fly their products. This $99 American military drone proved them wrong‚Äîit flies itself with one button and captures stunning 4K video.\n\nIt was created specifically for the US Special Forces by Captain Adam Scott, a 44-year-old US Army officer and lead engineer. He and his team were assigned to develop cutting-edge optical equipment for a critical mission in the Middle East. The mission required the Special Forces to capture enemy positions from miles away without ever being detected.\n\nAfter months of intense research and development, they created a groundbreaking prototype. The results were incredible. It was celebrated as the most successful military invention in recent years. It was the first to ever use the patented MOT military optical technology, meaning it''s at least 20 times more powerful than any commercially available drone. This gives it incredible capability.\n\nIt can literally capture anything from miles away with stunning 4K quality.\n\nAfter seeing the incredible potential of this new technology, Adam quickly realized the impact this device could have on the general public. So he decided to make this device available to anyone who wants to try it. As the original creator of the technology, he secured all the permissions needed to redevelop the device and ready it for mass production.\n\nHe called it GhostWing, and it''s the most powerful drone ever made.\n\nIt uses a combination of military-grade nanotechnology and unique composite materials to achieve the level of quality of top drone models, but for a fraction of the price. Adam developed his own software that increases the drone''s power and control by 120%%, making it a true one-button drone that literally anyone can fly on their very first try.\n\nIt''s loaded with cutting-edge technology like the Follow Me feature, which lets you take amazing videos of yourself without even touching the controller. The advanced GPS functionality means it can track your location within 900 meters and return to you quickly if the signal is weak or the battery gets low. You never have to worry about losing it.\n\nThe collision detection function prevents any accidental crash or damage, making this drone the safest quadcopter ever engineered. It''s literally impossible to crash. And because it''s made of the best military materials available, it''s virtually indestructible. It''s completely waterproof and strong enough to withstand both freezing cold and scorching hot temperatures.\n\nAnd what''s best about this drone is that you can use it for thousands of different purposes. Whether you''re excited about turning your social media profile into a viral sensation, or you want to capture precious memories with your family, the possibilities with the GhostWing are endless. It''s also a perfect security tool, allowing you to monitor your property from a safe distance.\n\nWhen Adam first launched GhostWing, it spread like wildfire in the military community. What he didn''t expect was for everyone to start sharing the incredible footage they shot with the GhostWing all over the internet. After going viral, it sold out within the first 48 hours and quickly developed a waitlist of over 10,000 orders from all around the world. Celebrities, professional photographers, and filmmakers have all made the switch to it.\n\nAdam wants everyone to know about this new technology, so he has tripled production and is offering a 50%% discount for anyone who orders within the next 24 hours. You can get even deeper discounts by ordering multiple GhostWings, making it a perfect gift for anyone.\n\nMy advice: grab one for yourself and a few more for your friends and family before this amazing deal is taken down. Click on the link below this video to visit the official website and order with 50%% off.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1046, '2026-01-18T09:01:26.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recuFEGVqamtAsU1s', 'VitalTac - Script 1036 - Nick', 'rec3cJmt5H4AENEgZ', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('Amazon just permanently banned this flashlight. Not because it''s defective. Not because of a recall. Because it''s too powerful for civilians to own. And now half a million people are trying to get one before the government shuts it down completely.\n\nTwo weeks ago, a Special Forces veteran posted a video demonstrating what this military flashlight can actually do. He pointed it at a piece of cardboard, and it caught fire in 10 seconds. From pure light. He aimed it at a wall 2 miles away, and it lit up like it was noon. The video hit 40 million views. And 48 hours later, Amazon pulled every listing and sent the manufacturer a permanent ban notice.\n\nThink about that. Amazon sells tasers. They sell pepper spray. They sell crossbows. But this flashlight ‚Äî this is what they said was too dangerous.\n\nHere''s what makes it different from every flashlight you''ve ever held. Standard tactical flashlights push maybe 1,000 lumens. This one uses military-grade Cree LED technology that produces a beam at least 20 times more powerful than anything on the commercial market. It was originally designed for American Special Forces conducting close-quarters combat in total darkness ‚Äî where the flashlight wasn''t just a tool, it was a weapon. At hallway distance, it completely overwhelms human vision. Anyone caught in the beam is instantly blind, disoriented, and unable to function. Fights over. No contact required.\n\nThis technology was restricted to active-duty Special Forces until a decorated combat veteran ‚Äî three tours, multiple commendations ‚Äî came home and made a decision that changed everything. He''d used these flashlights in the most dangerous environments on the planet, and he couldn''t stop thinking about one thing: his family had nothing even close to this for protection at home. He memorized the design. Built a prototype. The military''s legal team showed up at his door within a week. So he redesigned it ‚Äî every component modified to be completely legal for civilian ownership, but with every tactical function preserved. He called it VitalTac. And it''s the reason Amazon is panicking right now.\n\nVitalTac is built from the same aerospace-grade aluminum and titanium used on F-35 fighter jets. You can use it as a strike weapon in close quarters and it won''t scratch. It''s waterproof to 100 meters. It operates in extreme cold and extreme heat. You can drop it off a building, run it over with a truck ‚Äî it doesn''t care. It fires up instantly every single time because when you hear glass break at 2 AM, the thing you grab can''t have a failure mode.\n\nThe tactical strobe does exactly what it does for SWAT teams ‚Äî it neurologically overloads anyone caught in it, buying you the seconds you need to move your family, get to a phone, or take a defensive position. The SOS mode is visible from aircraft at distance for large-scale emergencies.\n\nNow here''s why you''re seeing this ad and not just finding it on Amazon. The US Product Safety Commission is finalizing paperwork to reclassify VitalTac as military-grade defense equipment. That means civilian sales end. Not reduced. Not restricted. Ended. The only reason you can still get one right now is that the manufacturer sells directly through their own website ‚Äî and they''ve already said when the regulation passes, they comply immediately.\n\nToday, VitalTac is available at 50%% off. Not because it''s a sale ‚Äî because the manufacturer wants to get as many into civilian hands as possible before the window closes. Click the link now. Because after that Amazon ban and 40 million views, the only people who won''t have one are the people who saw this and scrolled past it. Don''t be the person who watches the news six months from now wishing they''d clicked.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1036, '2026-01-30T16:49:03.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recuFRHgAWPlLRxEY', 'GhostWing - Script 1022 - Nick', 'recMS4kpPubp6bHyu', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('If you''re over 50 and you''ve ever wanted to capture stunning aerial footage of your grandkids, your property, or your family gatherings‚Äîbut you assumed drones were too complicated, too fragile, or too much of a headache to bother with‚Äîyou need to hear what happened to a retired firefighter named Tom.\nSee, Tom spent 30 years running into burning buildings while everyone else ran out. Exposed himself to smoke, heat, and danger so strangers could see their families again. When he finally retired, he didn''t ask for much. He just wanted to capture his grandkids'' soccer games from the air. Those sweeping cinematic shots. The kind that make ordinary Saturday mornings look like something worth remembering forever.\nSo he did what any reasonable person would do. He went online, did his research, read the reviews, and bought a drone. Three hundred dollars. Top brand. The box said "beginner-friendly" in big bold letters.\nWhat a lie.\nFirst flight, Tom pressed the button and that thing screamed to life like a chainsaw fighting a blender. His six-year-old grandson dropped his juice box, covered his ears, and ran inside crying. Soccer game over. Memory ruined.\nTom figured he just needed practice. So he tried again the next weekend.\nSecond flight, a light breeze rolled through. Maybe ten miles an hour. Nothing. But that drone started convulsing in the air like a drunk hummingbird having a seizure. Tom pulled out his phone to watch the footage later. Looked like he filmed it during an earthquake. Completely unusable. Embarrassing.\nHe wasn''t going to quit. Thirty years of running into fires taught him persistence.\nThird flight. He was careful this time. Stayed low. Avoided the wind. Then a gust pushed it sideways into a tree branch. The drone dropped from the sky, hit his driveway, and exploded into a dozen plastic pieces.\nThree hundred dollars. Exposed wires and shattered plastic.\nHis wife came outside and found him standing there, staring at the wreckage. She didn''t say anything. She didn''t have to. Tom already felt like an idiot.\nBut here''s what really got to him. It wasn''t the money.\nIt was that instruction manual. Fifty-three pages of tiny print clearly written by someone who hates human beings. An app that crashed twice before he could even pair it. Buttons so small his fingers‚Äîthe same fingers that pulled people from burning cars‚Äîcouldn''t even press them without hitting three things at once.\nTom wasn''t stupid. He saved lives for three decades. He ran complex rescue operations. But this drone made him feel like a confused old man who couldn''t keep up with technology.\nAnd that made him furious.\nSo he started digging. Reading forums. Watching videos. And then he called up his buddy Ray. Ray spent twenty years flying surveillance drones for the military before he retired. Classified stuff. The real deal.\nTom asked him straight: "Why are these things so terrible?"\nRay laughed. Then he told Tom something that changed everything.\nTurns out, the technology for silent, rock-solid, impossible-to-crash drone flight has existed for over a decade. The military has it. Hollywood has it. News crews covering war zones have it.\nBut the big drone companies? They keep it locked away in machines that cost five, eight, even ten thousand dollars. And even those require weeks of training to fly properly.\nWhy? Because they make more money selling you garbage that breaks, then selling you the "upgraded" garbage next year. Planned obsolescence. Repeat customers. It''s not incompetence. It''s strategy.\nThey don''t want you to have a drone that lasts forever and flies perfectly on day one. That''s bad for business.\nBut Ray told Tom about something new. Something that was about to blow up their entire racket.\nA small team of engineers‚Äîthree of them retired military, two of them grandparents‚Äîgot fed up with watching their friends and family waste money on junk. So they went rogue. They took the same stabilization technology used in classified military operations and figured out how to miniaturize it. Pack it into something the size of a water bottle. Make it affordable. And most importantly, make it so simple that anyone‚Äîand they meant anyone‚Äîcould fly it on their very first try.\nNo training. No manual. No apps crashing. No tiny buttons.\nThey call it the Ghost Wing.\nAnd it''s about to make a lot of billionaire drone executives very, very angry.\nHere''s what makes the Ghost Wing different from every overpriced, overhyped, overcomplicated piece of junk collecting dust in your closet right now:\nFirst, it''s silent.\nNot "quieter than other drones." Silent. The brushless motor technology came directly from covert military reconnaissance units where any sound could get soldiers killed. They engineered noise out of existence.\nYou can fly the Ghost Wing ten feet above your grandson''s birthday party and the kids won''t even look up. No screaming. No crying. No ruined moments. Just smooth, invisible flight capturing everything.\nSecond, it doesn''t shake.\nThe triple-axis gyroscopic stabilization system locks onto its position like a hawk hunting prey. Wind gusts that would send other drones spinning into your neighbor''s swimming pool? The Ghost Wing doesn''t flinch. Doesn''t wobble. Doesn''t drift.\nYour footage comes out smooth as a Hollywood crane shot. Every single time. Even if your hands are shaking. Even if the wind is blowing. Even if you have no idea what you''re doing.\nThird, it survives your mistakes.\nThe reinforced polymer frame was designed for combat conditions. Drop it from fifty feet onto concrete. Crash it into your garage door. Clip a tree branch and watch it tumble into the bushes.\nPick it up. Turn it on. It flies away like nothing happened.\nOne early tester‚Äîa 68-year-old grandfather from Ohio‚Äîcrashed his Ghost Wing into his toolshed on his third flight. Dented the aluminum siding. The drone had a tiny scuff mark. He''s still flying it two years later.\nYou cannot kill this thing.\nAnd fourth‚Äîthis is the one that matters most‚Äîanyone can fly it.\nNot "anyone with practice." Not "anyone who watches the tutorials." Anyone. Period.\nTom''s wife Patricia is 72 years old. She''s never touched a drone. Never played a video game. Thought the whole thing was a waste of money.\nTom handed her the controller just to prove a point.\nThree minutes later, she had the Ghost Wing hovering over their backyard, filming their tomato garden from above, giggling like a kid on Christmas morning.\nHere''s why:\nOne button to take off. Press it. The Ghost Wing rises smoothly to exactly eight feet and hovers there, steady as a statue, waiting for you.\nOne button to land. Press it. Floats down soft as a feather and touches down right where it started.\nOne button to come home. Fly it over the trees, around the house, out of sight completely‚Äîdoesn''t matter. Press the button. It navigates itself back to you automatically. Every time. Without fail.\nThe controller was designed by the same team. Big buttons you can actually feel. A bright screen you can actually see in sunlight. Intuitive controls that make sense the first time you pick it up.\nNo squinting. No fumbling. No calling your teenager for help.\nYou''ll be teaching your grandkids how to fly it. Not the other way around.\nThe camera captures everything in stunning 4K ultra-high definition. The same resolution you see in nature documentaries on Netflix. The same clarity professional filmmakers pay tens of thousands of dollars to achieve.\nExcept now, you''re the director.\nYour grandson''s touchdown catch. Your granddaughter''s dance recital in the backyard. The family reunion with everyone waving up at the sky. Your property from angles you''ve never seen in thirty years of living there.\nThese aren''t just videos. These are heirlooms. The kind of footage your great-grandchildren will watch someday and say, "Look, there''s Grandpa. He filmed this himself."\nNow here''s where things get interesting.\nWhen the Ghost Wing team finished their prototype, they had a choice. They could sell out to one of the big drone companies. Take the buyout. Let the technology get locked away in a ten-thousand-dollar machine nobody could afford.\nThey said no.\nInstead, they decided to sell direct. No retail markup. No middlemen taking their cut. No billion-dollar marketing budget to pay for.\nJust engineers who built something incredible selling it straight to the people who need it.\nThe big companies tried to stop them. Threatened lawsuits. Pressured suppliers. One distributor got a call from a lawyer the day before they were supposed to ship.\nDidn''t work.\nThe Ghost Wing is here. And right now, while they build awareness and take market share from the giants, they''re offering something that won''t last forever:\nFifty percent off.\nHalf price for a drone that outperforms machines costing ten times as much‚Äîand is a hundred times easier to fly.\nAt this price, you''re not paying for their marketing. You''re not paying for their Super Bowl commercials. You''re not paying for their CEO''s third yacht.\nYou''re paying for the technology. Nothing else.\nBut they can''t keep this up forever.\nThe last four shipments sold out in 72 hours or less. The specialized silent motors come from a single factory in Taiwan and they can only produce so many per month. Once this batch is gone, the price goes back up. No exceptions.\nIf you''re reading this and the button below still works, there''s still stock available. If it doesn''t, you''ll have to join the waiting list for the next shipment.\nAnd here''s the part that makes this whole thing completely risk-free:\nYou''re protected for a full 90 days.\nThree entire months. A full season. That''s how long you have to put the Ghost Wing through absolute hell.\nFly it in the wind. Crash it into things. Let your spouse try it. Let your grandkids try it. Take it to the beach, the park, the lake house. Film everything.\nIf it doesn''t blow your mind. If your footage doesn''t make your friends grab your arm and ask, "How the hell did you do that?" If you don''t find yourself reaching for it every single weekend just to see what you can capture next.\nSend it back.\nFull refund. No questions. No restocking fees. No hassle. Just a simple return and your money back in your account.\n90 days. That''s how confident they are that once you fly this thing, you''ll never look at another drone again.\nTom''s got one now.\nUses it every single weekend. Sometimes twice. He''s got footage of his grandkids that looks like it belongs in a movie. Last Thanksgiving, he flew it over the whole family in his brother''s backyard. Thirty-two relatives waving up at the sky. They watched the footage together after dinner and his daughter cried.\nHis grandkids fight over who gets to sit with him and watch the videos. They call him "Papa Hollywood" now.\nThat three-hundred-dollar name-brand drone that exploded on his driveway? Tom kept the box. Uses it to store old batteries in the garage.\nPatricia‚Äîhis 72-year-old wife who thought drones were a waste of money‚Äîshe''s already planning her spring garden video. She wants to film the tulips coming up from above.\nTom says it''s the best purchase he''s made since he retired.\nClick below to check if the Ghost Wing is still available at the 50%% discount.\nThis military-grade silent drone is selling faster than they can make them. Once this batch is gone, so is the price.\nDon''t let satisfying satisfying moments slip away because some corporation decided the technology was too good for regular people.\nYou spent your whole life working. Building. Sacrificing.\nYou''ve earned the right to capture what matters‚Äîwithout fighting a machine to do it.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1022, '2026-01-11T18:42:27.000Z');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO video_scripts (id, script_name, product_id, author_id, script_content, is_approved, needs_revision, version, notes, hook, body, hook_number, base_script_number, created_at) VALUES ('recv9kNvsbvh4QQXG', 'GhostWing - Script 1061 - Nick', 'recMS4kpPubp6bHyu', 'recaidhXBfNk3aUQI', printf('I''ve owned four drones. Crashed every single one ‚Äî expensive ones, cheap ones, didn''t matter, they all ended up in pieces in my backyard. Then my buddy at the VFW handed me this $99 military drone and said "try to break it." I still can''t.\n\nHere''s why. A 44-year-old US Army officer named Captain Adam Scott ‚Äî not a Silicon Valley kid, a real engineer who''s been downrange ‚Äî got assigned to develop something the Special Forces desperately needed for a critical mission in the Middle East. They had to capture enemy positions from miles away without ever being detected. No room for error. No second chances. After months of grinding R&D, Adam and his team built a prototype that command celebrated as the most successful military optical invention in recent years.\n\nThe secret is something called patented MOT military optical technology. It makes this thing at least 20 times more powerful than any drone you''ll find at Best Buy or Amazon. We''re talking crystal-clear 4K footage from tens of miles out. The kind of imagery that used to cost the Pentagon a fortune ‚Äî now packed into a frame that folds smaller than a water bottle and runs 70%% quieter than any standard drone on the market.\n\nAdam looked at what he''d built and knew it was too good to lock inside a classified program. He secured every permission needed, redesigned it for civilian hands, and put it into mass production himself. No corporate middlemen. No $800 markup. Just the guy who invented it selling it directly to people like you and me.\n\nHe called it GhostWing, and it is the most powerful drone ever made available to the public.\n\nAdam developed his own software that increases power and control by 120%%, which means my 74-year-old neighbor flew it on his first try. The "follow me" feature shoots stunning video of you without touching the controller ‚Äî my daughter used it to film my grandkids'' entire Christmas morning from angles I never dreamed possible. Advanced GPS tracks your location within 900 meters and brings it right back to your hand when the signal weakens or the battery gets low. The collision detection means you will not crash this thing ‚Äî I''ve tried. Trust me. Built from military-grade carbon-polymer materials, it''s completely waterproof and handles freezing winters and brutal summer heat without flinching. It flies a 2.7-mile range on a 15-minute flight time, which covers more ground than most people''s entire property.\n\nThis is what changed everything for me. Last spring I had a bad storm rip through. Instead of paying a contractor $300 to climb up and tell me what I already suspected, I sent the GhostWing up and inspected every inch of my roof in four minutes. I survey my whole property line before breakfast now. I keep an eye on my land, my outbuildings, my driveway ‚Äî all from my back porch. The peace of mind alone is worth ten times what I paid.\n\nWhen Adam first launched GhostWing, it spread through the military community like wildfire. Then people started posting their footage online and it exploded. Sold out in 48 hours flat. Over 10,000 orders stacked up on the waitlist. Celebrities and professional filmmakers quietly made the switch. It''s now sitting at over 15,000 five-star reviews from regular folks who can''t believe what they''re getting for this price.\n\nAdam has tripled production and right now he''s offering 50%% off for anyone who orders within the next 24 hours. You can stack even deeper discounts by ordering multiple GhostWings ‚Äî one for you, one for your son, one for your buddy who still thinks drones are too complicated. Every order comes with a 30-day money-back guarantee, so there is zero risk.\n\nClick the link below this video, go to the official site, and grab yours at 50%% off before this deal disappears.'), 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1061, '2026-02-18T16:15:14.000Z');
